  "game_explanation": "In this 3-player, 2-chip-color bargaining game, each player starts with 10 RED and 10 GREEN chips. GREEN is common-value at $0.50 for everyone, so it is obviously the high-value chip. RED is privately valued: dog=$0.30, cat=$0.40, buffalo=$0.10. From the analyst’s perspective, the efficient direction of trade is buffalo giving up RED (low value to him) to dog and especially to cat (for whom RED is relatively valuable), in exchange for some GREEN. However, players do not know each other's valuations; they see only their own and the public history. This creates uncertainty about whether others also value RED highly or consider it junk. Because all know GREEN’s fixed high value and RED’s possible range ($0.10–$1.00), everyone must infer others’ preferences from observed willingness to trade. Dog is cooperative and tolerant of small gains, cat is tougher but not extremely rejecting, and buffalo is strategic and numerate with medium fairness expectations. A core tension is that any favorable bilateral trade might be competitively accepted by the third player, since multiple acceptances lead to a random recipient. That discourages extremely generous offers to the group and favors offers that are just good enough for at least one expected partner. Over only 3 rounds (9 proposal turns), players have limited time to learn, so they are likely to try modest, gainful trades with relatively symmetric surplus splits and to avoid large speculative exchanges that could backfire. The likely pattern is: buffalo repeatedly tries to monetize his low-value RED by buying GREEN; cat is cautious about giving up GREEN but will trade if the RED/ GREEN rate is strongly in his favor; dog tests slightly more cooperative ratios, occasionally making trades that yield small but positive value gains. Because GREEN is so valuable and the horizon is short, no one wants to give up many GREENs without multiple REDs in return; trades that clear tend to be ones where buffalo pays several REDs per GREEN, especially to cat, while dog’s proposals in early rounds are often declined until players infer who actually values RED most.",
