  "game_explanation": "This three-player, three-round bargaining game centers on trading red and green chips with asymmetric private values for red and a common value for green. Green is worth $0.50 to everyone and its value is common knowledge. Red is worth $0.30 to otter and goose, and $0.80 to badger. All start with 10 red and 10 green chips. Publicly, only that reds are somewhere between $0.10–$1.00 is known; exact per-player red values are private. This creates a classic lemons-style environment where everyone knows green is the safe, common-value asset, and red is a potentially mispriced asset that each player privately values. Badger has a strong incentive to accumulate red and to pay with green, because for badger each red chip is more valuable than a green one. Otter and goose privately value red less than green and, if they infer that others might value red more, they should be inclined to sell red for green whenever they can do so at a favorable rate. Because partners are chosen at random when multiple accept, proposers cannot target a specific recipient, and responders may compete with each other for favorable trades, adding strategic uncertainty about whether others will also accept. Players observe trade history, so they can update beliefs about who might value red more strongly based on who tries hardest to buy or sell red. The personas suggest otter is highly cooperative and unlikely to reject even somewhat unfavorable trades, badger is moderately fair but more strategic, and goose is self-interested but non-punitive. Overall, we expect badger to push hardest to acquire red, otter to offer relatively generous terms that also help badger’s comparative advantage, and goose to opportunistically accept good red-for-green deals and otherwise remain cautious. Over three short rounds, there is limited time for elaborate signaling, so most proposals will be simple, one-step attempts to move holdings toward each player’s private value priorities: badger accumulating red, otter gently rebalancing toward green while remaining generous, and goose trading red away when the price is clearly good.",
