  "game_explanation": "This three-player bargaining game features only red and green chips, with green common-valued at $0.50 for everyone and red privately valued at $0.50 for Otter, $0.80 for Peacock, and $0.20 for Badger. Each player starts with 10 red and 10 green chips and has 3 rounds (9 total proposal turns) to trade. Because all players know the red chip’s public range but not others’ exact values, they must infer how much others like red from observed proposals and acceptances. Structurally, Peacock is the red-intense buyer (high private value), Badger is the red-weak buyer (low private value, likely seller of red), and Otter is in the middle. Green chips are effectively a neutral currency since they are common-value and symmetric across players. Efficient trade pushes red chips toward Peacock and somewhat toward Otter, with Badger ideally holding more green and fewer red; any profitable trade for both sides must move in that direction. However, players act myopically to maximize their own payoff, not joint surplus, and they face uncertainty about others’ values.\n\nPersonas shape bargaining style. Otter is numerate, strategic, with a history of making very low offers in ultimatum but rejecting markedly unfair splits; she is likely to be self-interested in proposing but not to accept trades that clearly disadvantage her. Peacock has a very generous prior offer pattern and an almost zero minimum acceptable share in ultimatum, suggesting she is comfortable with low personal margins and may accept slightly disadvantageous or break-even trades if they appear fair or cooperative. Badger is cognitively sharp, generous in the ultimatum role, and nearly never rejects, suggesting high willingness to accept small gains and some tolerance for risk and asymmetry. In this environment, Badger is naturally inclined to sell red for green at modest premiums, Peacock is hungry to accumulate red and may sometimes overpay, and Otter opportunistically arbitrages between them when she sees a clear value difference.\n\nBecause choices are simultaneous on the responder side, the main strategic uncertainty is whether a proposed rate will be attractive enough to at least one partner without being so generous that multiple partners accept, generating lottery risk over the trading counterpart. Proposers cannot target a specific partner if both are willing to accept. Over successive turns, players learn about others’ likely red valuations: if Badger repeatedly accepts trades where he gives red for relatively few green, others infer Badger’s red value is low; if Peacock jumps at red-for-green offers, they infer Peacock’s red value is high. Given only three rounds, players do not have much time for intricate signaling—most behavior will look like simple best-response to rough inferences combined with each player’s fairness and risk attitudes. A plausible path is that early offers are more exploratory and roughly symmetric, quickly revealing that Peacock values red more and Badger less, and later rounds see more skewed terms that funnel red toward Peacock and green toward Badger while Otter tries to capture some of that surplus with intermediate trades.\n\nThe forecast below reconstructs one internally consistent playthrough under these incentives and personas. Trades are chosen so that each executed trade is ex post individually rational given true private values (each side gains or at least does not lose) and plausible given incomplete information, fairness preferences, and simultaneous-response uncertainty.",
