anding when accepting offers. Bear is highly cooperative and tolerant in ultimatum (very low minimum acceptable, low rejection rate), so she is likely to accept many slightly-profitable trades and to propose modestly favorable but not extreme offers. Hamster is less cooperative, more self-focused, and values fairness moderately; with high red value and relatively strict thresholds, he is willing to pay for red if needed but will strongly resist trades that feel lopsided against him and is unlikely to accept small or negative gains.\n\nOver three rounds, with each player proposing once per round, we expect early proposals to be exploratory and somewhat conservative: pig attempts to profit by exporting low-value red for green, bear looks for gentle improvements that others might reliably accept, and hamster, knowing his strong preference for red, tries to acquire red at rates that he views as fair while leveraging his low cooperativeness in acceptance decisions. As the history of accepts and declines accumulates, later rounds incorporate learning: players revise beliefs about others’ willingness to trade red for green and adjust prices accordingly. However, with only three rounds and the random partner-selection rule when multiple players accept, there is persistent uncertainty about who will be matched and about the exact valuations of others. This leads to relatively simple, incremental proposals rather than highly optimized, fully revealing trades.",
