simple trades (often 1–3 chips) that are plausibly beneficial under a wide range of opponent valuations. Over time, acceptance or rejection provides Bayesian evidence about others’ preferences. However, the game is short—only three rounds and one proposal per player per round—so there is limited time for sophisticated signaling or reputation building. Instead, players will likely stick to straightforward, roughly fair-looking offers that appear beneficial to at least one counterparty and not obviously harmful to the other.\n\nA key dynamic is multi-recipient competition: if both non-senders accept, the recipient is chosen randomly. Proposers cannot target the best-fitting partner once offers are out, so overly attractive offers run the risk of being accepted by the less-profitable partner from the proposer’s perspective. This encourages somewhat moderate offers that are acceptable to at least one partner but not so generous that both always jump in. At the same time, because these players are moderately to highly cooperative, we expect relatively high acceptance rates for clearly individually profitable trades, especially from gorilla.\n\nOver the three rounds, we should see: (1) early, conservative testing trades, often involving kangaroo selling RED for GREEN to gauge how much others value RED; (2) fox gradually trying to amass RED when the terms look favorable relative to the safe $0.50 GREEN value; and (3) gorilla acting as a flexible, cooperative counterparty, sometimes accepting trades that marginally favor others but still leave him better off in value terms. Uncertainty about private RED values and about the others’ willingness to accept modestly unequal deals will constrain extreme or exploitative offers; instead, the game is likely to display moderately balanced trades that move RED toward fox and GREEN toward kangaroo, with gorilla adjusting opportunistically.",
