ate RED. Gorilla is the most generous and least rejection-prone, with a history of accepting even very low personal shares: he is likely to accept many offers that are even slightly favorable or almost neutral, especially if they look fair or cooperative.\n\nStrategically, senders must anticipate that if they make a good deal for both high-RED-value players, both could accept, leading to random partner selection. That weakens any attempt to target a specific counterpart. Over the three rounds (nine total proposal turns), we expect early offers to be exploratory (simple 1-for-1 RED-GREEN swaps around perceived fairness), with later offers becoming slightly more tailored as players infer that others like RED too. Fox is likely to test 1 RED for 2 GREEN early (aiming for obvious personal gain but risking low acceptance from gorilla), while kangaroo and gorilla will tend to propose trades that gain them RED but remain moderate enough to induce acceptance from fox. Because GREEN is common-value and useful to everyone, no one wants to deplete GREEN entirely, but kangaroo and gorilla will be more willing to spend GREEN to build a RED advantage over the limited three rounds. Overall, the game likely yields modest RED reallocation toward kangaroo and gorilla through a mix of slightly favorable and roughly fair trades, with some declined attempts where fox pushes too hard or where a buyer asks fox to part with RED too cheaply.",
