  "game_explanation": "All three players start with symmetric chip holdings (10 RED, 10 BLUE, 10 GREEN) but highly asymmetric private values for RED and BLUE. GREEN is common-value at $0.50 for everyone, so it is a natural currency for early trades and a safe benchmark: any PLAYER will rarely want to give up more than $0.50 of value per GREEN they relinquish.\n\nPrivate values:\n- alligator-blue-3197 (Alligator): BLUE=$0.60, GREEN=$0.50, RED=$0.30. Alligator likes BLUE slightly more than GREEN, and RED the least.\n- lion-orange-6194 (Lion): BLUE=$1.00, GREEN=$0.50, RED=$0.40. Lion strongly prefers BLUE; GREEN is moderate; RED is least.\n- iguana-orange-3232 (Iguana): BLUE=$0.40, GREEN=$0.50, RED=$0.80. Iguana strongly prefers RED; GREEN is moderate; BLUE is least.\n\nThus, efficient direction of trade is:\n- From Iguana to Lion: BLUE (worth $0.40 to Iguana, $1.00 to Lion).\n- From Lion to Iguana: RED (worth $0.40 to Lion, $0.80 to Iguana).\n- From Alligator to Lion/Iguana: small adjustments in BLUE/RED that exploit $0.30 vs $0.40/$0.80 spreads.\n\nHowever, no player knows the others’ values, only the coarse public range (RED/BLUE between $0.10 and $1.00, GREEN fixed at $0.50). Each must infer others’ preferences from observed trades. Given ultimatum-task priors, all three are relatively tolerant and unlikely to reject mildly disadvantageous offers, especially Iguana (very low minimum acceptable and rejection rate). Lion is analytically strong and values BLUE highly, so is likely to make more aggressive BLUE-acquisition proposals and to accept trades that give BLUE even at slightly worse than fair rates from her own perspective, as long as there is net gain. Alligator is older, more cooperative and uncertainty-averse, so will tend to propose and accept conservative, modest-gain trades rather than very sharp exploitative ones.\n\nStrategic uncertainty is driven by three main factors: (1) who values which color most, (2) competition for being the chosen counterparty when multiple accept, and (3) finite horizons (3 rounds × 3 turns) that limit the chance to correct mistakes. Players must weigh whether to accept a mediocre but positive trade now versus waiting for a better opportunity that may not come. Because responses are simultaneous and the realized recipient is random when multiple accept, a player might decline a marginally good offer if they think another player will also accept and reduce their chances of actually getting the deal.\n\nAcross the full game, a plausible path is that early trades are somewhat exploratory and conservative, often using GREEN as the payment medium. As patterns emerge—especially if someone persistently buys one color—others start inferring that color is particularly valuable to that player and adjust their acceptance thresholds or proposal design. Given the time limit and players’ cooperative priors, the game is likely to see several accepted trades that move RED toward Iguana, BLUE toward Lion, and some BLUE from Alligator to Lion, with GREEN pieces used to balance perceived fairness. However, incomplete information and random recipient selection lead to some declined or mis-targeted offers, particularly when proposed rates are too extreme relative to what others guess about fair value.",
