ect exploratory offers: bear and others test exchange rates like 1 red for 1 blue or 2 green for 1 blue to see who bites. Across the three rounds, some mutually beneficial trades likely execute, building weak signals about preferences: if Goose readily accepts trades where she gains red, others may infer she values red; if Ram quickly accepts trades giving up red for blue, others may infer he values blue slightly more than red. With just three rounds, there is limited time to fully learn or converge to fully efficient allocations, so players will lean toward simple, low-friction offers that roughly align with plausible common-value assumptions (e.g., reds and blues both assumed near the middle of the public range) rather than fully exploiting all theoretical surplus.\n\nGiven this combination of incentives, priors, and the short time horizon, we forecast: (1) Bear frequently tries to pick up blue or green by giving up red, sometimes at fairly generous terms; (2) Goose actively seeks red and occasionally blue, giving up green or sometimes blue when the rate seems reasonable; (3) Ram looks for small but safe positive gains and is ready to accept trades where he modestly improves his portfolio, especially if risk or complexity is low. Not all proposals will be accepted; some will be declined when they look one-sided or confusing given the limited information. Over three rounds, a small set of trades is likely executed, mostly moving some red toward Goose and some blue/green away from Bear and Ram in exchange for red or green.",
