itive person, he probably avoids extremely one-sided looking proposals—yet will reject trades that clearly hurt him.\n\nStrategically, uncertainty about others’ valuations combines with the random-matching feature when multiple players accept: a proposer cannot target a specific partner once more than one is willing to accept. That discourages proposals that are highly attractive to both counterparts unless the proposer is indifferent between partners, and it encourages slightly tailored offers that one counterpart is more likely to find attractive. Over three rounds (nine proposal turns), players gradually learn from who accepts or rejects what, but incentives remain strongly individual: everyone maximizes own value, not collective surplus. Early in the game, trades are more exploratory yet still roughly fair by the public ranges; later, if patterns emerge (e.g., someone repeatedly trying to offload a color), others might infer that color is low-value to that player and adjust terms accordingly. Given the symmetric starting inventories and limited horizon, players are unlikely to fully separate types, but they can reach several mutually beneficial exchanges, especially around Lion’s weak blue and Owl’s weak red.\n\nThe specific forecast below assumes: (1) modest, not fully optimized rationality; (2) offers that usually give the counterparty weakly positive value ex ante given public ranges; (3) Ram and Owl enforcing a medium fairness standard similar to their ultimatum behavior; and (4) Lion being relatively easy to satisfy, accepting even small gains. This yields a game with a few successful trades that move chips toward each player’s strengths, mixed with some declined proposals that are perceived as too thin or poorly targeted under uncertainty.",
