  "game_explanation": "This three-player, multi-round chip-bargaining game features privately known values for red, blue, and purple chips, with green chips having a known common value of $0.50 each. All players start with 10 of each color. Because green is common-value and mid-priced, it becomes a natural medium of exchange: everyone knows it is safe to give or receive at $0.50. The real strategic tension lies in red, blue, and purple chips, where each player only knows their own valuations and must infer others’ values from observed trades.\n\nValuations:\n- Dolphin: BLUE 0.80, GREEN 0.50, RED 0.50, PURPLE 0.30\n- Owl: BLUE 0.70, GREEN 0.50, PURPLE 0.40, RED 0.40\n- Whale: RED 0.90, PURPLE 0.60, BLUE 0.70, GREEN 0.50\n\nPrivately, dolphin strongly prefers blue, is indifferent between red and green, and likes purple least. Owl values blue most, then purple, and likes red least. Whale values red highest, then purple, then blue. Thus, in terms of relative advantage, whale has especially strong demand for red and moderate for purple; dolphin and owl have high demand for blue; dolphin is especially happy to offload purple; owl is more willing than dolphin to hold purple; dolphin is willing to trade red away for blue, while whale is willing to pay a premium for red.\n\nGiven the ultimatum-task priors, dolphin tends to be tolerant of low payoffs (very low minimum acceptable, almost never rejects) and not especially generous as a proposer. Owl is cooperative and empathic, with very low rejection thresholds and moderately fair offers. Whale has higher cognitive sophistication, some willingness to reject low offers, and very high uncertainty aversion, suggesting more cautious, value-based decisions and a bit more sensitivity to fairness or to avoiding dominated trades.\n\nOver three rounds, each player proposes once per round in a fixed order. They must offer one color and request a different color, with the risk that if both others accept, the partner is selected at random. This creates uncertainty for targeted trades: if you design a trade primarily for whale (who loves red), owl might also accept, and the realized partner may not be the intended one. Players also face dynamic constraints: chip inventories change immediately, so an early advantageous trade can open later opportunities (e.g., accumulating blue to later swap for something else), while a poor early trade can leave someone stuck with low-value colors.\n\nGiven the short horizon (3 rounds, 9 turns total) and the players’ priors, we expect:\n- Use of green as a safe currency, especially early, because it is common-value and psychologically low risk.\n- Dolphin making value-seeking but not very generous offers, often trying to trade away purple for blue or red, and being very accepting of trades that yield even modest gains.\n- Owl being willing to facilitate trades that seem roughly reasonable, with a mild fairness orientation but a low rejection threshold.\n- Whale being more selective: likely to accept clearly beneficial red-acquisition deals, and more cautious with purple and blue unless the gain is clear.\n\nBecause no one sees others’ valuations, their behavior is guided by simple value heuristics (\"I want more of my high-value colors, I can spare my low-value ones\") and inferred demand (e.g., if someone repeatedly offers a color, maybe they value it less). Over one game, it is likely that some trades occur that are mutually beneficial but not fully surplus-maximizing, and some potentially Pareto-improving trades do not happen due to uncertainty or misaligned expectations.",
