ishments.\n\nPersonas and ultimatum-style priors shape tactics: dolphin was previously very generous as a proposer and only moderately strict as a responder, suggesting she may make relatively fair, symmetric-looking offers and be willing to accept moderately beneficial trades rather than hold out. Duck and alligator both showed low minimum acceptable and low rejection rates in ultimatum, indicating they’re inclined to accept most deals that look at least modestly profitable and don’t insist on high fairness thresholds. This makes the environment relatively cooperative: once a somewhat favorable rate appears, it is likely to be accepted. Over the three rounds, we expect early exploratory proposals that reveal some structure of preferences (who really wants red, who is willing to shed purple or green), followed by more targeted trades that move chips toward their highest-value owners, especially red to duck and purple to duck/alligator, while dolphin tries to upgrade purple into red or green.\n\nThe forecasted play below reflects one plausible negotiation path where players use their private values, rough fairness instincts, and observed history to craft mutually beneficial but not fully optimized trades under uncertainty about others’ exact valuations.",
