een as the payment currency. Because responses are simultaneous and multiple acceptances trigger random partner selection, senders cannot perfectly target a specific recipient. This uncertainty encourages offers that are at least non-terrible for any plausible taker. Over time, observed acceptances or rejections inform rough inferences about others’ preferences (e.g., if Lion eagerly accepts trades for PURPLE or BLUE, that hints at high value on those chips). However, with only three rounds and three turns per round, there is limited time to converge to highly optimized trading patterns.\n\nGiven the personas and values, Camel is likely to aim for modest surplus and relatively cooperative trades, often moving from colors they value less (BLUE, maybe RED) into PURPLE and GREEN. Squid will try to accumulate BLUE and some GREEN, offloading PURPLE and RED when possible, and tends to propose reasonable splits that others can accept. Lion aims to convert RED (and potentially some GREEN) into BLUE and PURPLE but is more selective about trades that reduce their access to those high-value colors. Across the three rounds, we expect a handful of small, roughly value-improving trades rather than aggressive exploitation, with occasional declined offers when a proposer misjudges how costly a requested chip is to another player.",
