 thresholds in ultimatum tasks, so they are inclined to accept modest gains and to be relatively flexible. Badger, by contrast, has a very high rejection rate and high fairness sensitivity: he tends to reject offers he sees as too unfavorable, even at a cost to himself. That suggests badger will make relatively generous offers when he is the proposer (to ensure acceptance and feel fair), but will also readily reject trades that give him only small gains or feel exploitive.\n\nStrategically, butterfly, as first proposer each round and with relatively balanced valuations, is likely to experiment with small, seemingly fair exchanges that she believes others might accept, often using GREEN as a neutral currency and RED/BLUE as somewhat attractive to others. Badger will try to accumulate BLUE and RED while parting with GREEN or PURPLE, but will avoid trades where he yields too much of his high-value chips. Cat will look to offload RED (low value for her) and, to a lesser extent, PURPLE, in exchange for BLUE or GREEN. Because multiple acceptances lead to a random recipient, proposers cannot perfectly target one partner; they must design offers that would be acceptable to at least one counterpart while considering that either counterpart may be matched.\n\nAcross the three rounds, inventories will shift gradually. Early turns are exploratory, revealing who is eager to trade and which chip colors others seem to accept or decline. Later turns may become slightly more aggressive as players recognize remaining opportunities (e.g., badger pushing harder to get BLUE, or cat trying to dump last RED chips). However, the horizon is too short for elaborate dynamic strategies, so simple myopic value-improving trades dominate: each player asks, chip by chip, whether the incoming chip value exceeds the outgoing chip value by a comfortable margin, with badger requiring a larger margin than butterfly or cat.",
