 constraints and dynamically changing holdings; (2) simultaneous responses where a proposer risks trades going to a different recipient than intended; and (3) limited rounds (three rounds, three turns each), which constrain how long players can wait for perfect deals. Over the game, we expect early-round exploratory trades with relatively transparent, close-to-green-exchange rates to learn about others’ appetites, followed by slightly more targeted, surplus-extracting offers—especially with owl trying to accumulate red and purple from the others, while lion often acts as a liquidity provider using green and low-valued reds, and ram opportunistically trades purple and red when she can get strong value, but is willing to walk away from offers that feel too lopsided. Because no side payments or binding coalitions exist and multi-acceptance is randomized, proposers will often design offers that are at least acceptable to both potential recipients, but slightly more attractive to the one they infer cares more about the chip being sold.",
