 infer others' values from qualitative expectations (e.g., that others will also prefer at least one color and dislike another) and from any prior game experience (not modeled explicitly here, as this is treated as a standalone game). In the absence of precise knowledge, risk-averse or fairness-oriented participants tend to make modestly generous trades that are clearly good for themselves but likely at least weakly beneficial to others.\n\n3) **Finite horizon and proposer rotation:**\n- There are exactly three rounds, and each player proposes once per round. Early in the game, players can experiment with small trades that test counterparties' willingness to move particular colors. As the final round approaches, proposers face a use-it-or-lose-it pressure to secure at least one good trade, which encourages slightly more generous or simpler proposals that are more clearly acceptable.\n\nPersona priors suggest that all three players are relatively tolerant and cooperative, with low ultimatum rejection thresholds. Zebra has relatively high cognitive sophistication and high uncertainty aversion, so zebra is likely to design conservative offers that give the responder a visible gain while still improving zebra's own portfolio. Swan is analytically strong and highly cooperative; swan is likely to accept mild gains and to propose trades that are reasonably balanced rather than extremely one-sided. Dolphin has very low minimum acceptable and near-zero rejection tendency, plus a cooperative orientation; dolphin is therefore likely to accept many offers that provide even a small gain, and may make somewhat generous offers as a proposer.\n\nPutting this together, the likely bargaining pattern is that zebra will anchor the game with cautious, value-improving proposals focusing on unloading RED for BLUE or PURPLE or GREEN; swan will respond by trading away BLUE and occasionally GREEN to acquire RED and PURPLE when that seems beneficial; and dolphin, being highly accepting, will 