  "game_explanation": "All three players start with 10 of each chip color and know only their own values. Green is common-value at $0.50 for everyone, so it functions as a transparent numeraire and safe store of value. The private-value differences are strong on red, blue, and purple: turtle values purple the most among private chips but is generally low-value except for purple; hamster values purple and blue quite highly and red moderately; elephant values red the most and blue reasonably well but purple poorly. This creates natural comparative-advantage patterns: elephant wants to accumulate red and blue and shed purple; hamster wants purple and blue and is less eager for red; turtle wants purple (and green) but is willing to give up red and blue cheaply.\n\nHowever, the players do not see each other’s values and only observe trade behavior. Incentives over three rounds are to trade low-value colors for high-value colors when possible, but uncertainty about others’ preferences plus the random-resolution rule when multiple players accept limit aggressive underpricing: a sender cannot reliably target the best partner if both accept, which makes proposals more balanced and broadly acceptable rather than perfectly tailored. Turtle, with very low minimum acceptable ultimatum thresholds and high cooperation orientation, is likely to make generous, low-conflict offers aimed at securing at least some improvement and avoiding rejection, even if that sacrifices some surplus. Hamster and elephant have medium fairness thresholds and nontrivial rejection rates in the ultimatum task: they are less willing to accept highly lopsided trades that obviously disadvantage them, especially in early rounds, but they are not extremely tough. Both are reasonably numerate and can compare values across colors once they form hypotheses.\n\nDynamic uncertainty arises because proposal choices and acceptance patterns gradually reveal rough preferences. If elephant repeatedly offers purple away or eagerly accepts red, that signals their relative valuations to attentive others. Over three rounds, players have limited time to learn, so they are inclined to make proposals that are evidently beneficial or at least non-harmful to a broad range of possible opponent valuations (e.g., trading away a color they themselves dislike for a color they like, at modest exchange rates). The expected pattern is: early proposals are cautious and somewhat symmetric, aiming to test markets and avoid rejections; mid-game proposals respond to revealed preferences and may become more targeted as players infer who values which color; late in the third round, players are more willing to accept any trade that strictly raises their own value because there is no future punishment or continuation value. The equilibrating force is that all strongly prefer green to any likely low-valued private chip, so converting a low private-value color into green or into a clearly high-value color is attractive, while accepting trades that reduce green or one’s favorite color without adequate compensation will be resisted.\n\nGiven the personas, turtle tends to be the most accommodating and least rejection-prone, often designing trades with obvious win-win potential and being willing to accept slightly unequal but still positive trades. Hamster and elephant both reject transparently bad deals but are open to moderate gains. The three-round structure and fixed proposer sequence (turtle, then hamster, then elephant in each round) encourages early probing by turtle, midpoint adjustment by hamster, and more opportunistic, surplus-capturing moves by elephant, who goes last each round and can condition on prior actions. Overall, we expect a mix of accepted trades that gradually move red toward elephant and hamster, purple away from elephant and toward hamster and turtle, and some tentative rebalancing of green in exchange for high private-value colors when a partner seems eager enough.",
